Problem.Description:
Bob lives in Math Kingdom, there are N cities(numbered from 1 to N) and M roads in the kingdom. Each city has special cars which can take people from the city to any cities connected with it in certain ti hours, no matter how far or near they are. At the same time, every city has a Clock Number Ti. Now, we define function f(x), its value is the number of prime factors of x. Coincidentally, ti is equals to f(Ti). For example, if there is a bidirectional road from u to v, u’s Clock Number is 20, v’s Clock Number is 30, as we know that 20 = 2*2*5, 30 = 2*3*5, 2 and 5 are prime factors of 20, 2、3 and 5 are prime factors of 30, so f(20) = 2 and it costs 2 hours if Bob wants to go from u to v, f(30) = 3 and it costs 3 hours from v to u. Desert to “Math Kingdom”, isn’t it?
Here is the graph of sample input test case:

Bob wants to know the minimum time cost from city u to city v?
Problem.InputSpec:
The first line contains an integer T (T <= 11), denoting the number of the test cases.
For each test case, the first line contains, N(2 <= N <= 100) and M(N-1 <= M <= (N-1)*N/2), as mentioned above. The second line contains N integers, representing the clock number Ti(2 <= Ti <= 5000) of each city. The next M lines representing M roads, each line contains two integers u and v, means there is a road from u to v. After the M lines, there is a integer Q(0 <= Q <= 20), representing the pairs of cities Bob wants to query the minimum time cost. Then Q lines follow, each line two integers u and v, means Bob wants to know the minimum time cost from u to v. We guarantee that there is at least one way from city u to city v.
Problem.OutputSpec: For each query, output one integer in one line representing the minimum time cost from city u to city v.
